caption:
The stunning capture and removal of dictator Nicol√°s Maduro from Venezuela by the United States has raised many questions, including what comes next for the beleaguered South American nation.

We spoke to Juan Pablo Luna, the Diamond-Brown Chair in Democratic Studies in McGill‚Äôs Department of Political Science, to learn more. Link in bio.
firstComment:
Great article. I‚Äôm glad to see that McGill is covering developments in Venezuela. As a Venezuelan myself üáªüá™ and McGill alumn, I would like to share a few observations, given that the alarming tagline chosen for this post was ‚Äúthis is the international order falling apart.‚Äù

The prospect for democratization is not thin. A major blind spot in the article is that on July 28, 2024, the Venezuelan people chose to remove Nicol√°s Maduro through the democratic process, against all the odds (not allowing our elected leader Maria-Corona Machado to be on the ballot, no freedom of expression and under repression). After proving the opposition won, the regime, however, clung to power by force. In the aftermath, more than 2,000 people were incarcerated for protesting against the regime (let‚Äôs make it clear, regime, not government). 

Venezuelans, both inside and outside the country, are united in their desire for change. It is also important to acknowledge the presence of armed groups operating in Venezuela, the ones Chavez diabolically built and criminal organizations from Colombia and Hezbollah. We know it.

Great article. I‚Äôm glad to see that McGill is covering developments in Venezuela. As a Venezuelan myself üáªüá™ and McGill alumn, I would like to share a few observations, given that the alarming tagline chosen for this post was ‚Äúthis is the international order falling apart.‚Äù

The prospect for democratization is not thin. A major blind spot in the article is that on July 28, 2024, the Venezuelan people chose to remove Nicol√°s Maduro through the democratic process, against all the odds (not allowing our elected leader Maria-Corona Machado to be on the ballot, no freedom of expression and under repression). After proving the opposition won, the regime, however, clung to power by force. In the aftermath, more than 2,000 people were incarcerated for protesting against the regime (let‚Äôs make it clear, regime, not government). 

Venezuelans, both inside and outside the country, are united in their desire for change. It is also important to acknowledge the presence of armed groups operating in Venezuela, the ones Chavez diabolically built and criminal organizations from Colombia and Hezbollah. We know it.

Continued:
It is striking to hear discussions about the surgical removal of Maduro as evidence of the collapse of international order when, after 27 years of dictatorship, the world largely stood by. Venezuelans pursued the democratic route by participating in an election held under unfair conditions, gathered evidence of their victory, and yet meaningful international action did not follow. That is the TRUE collapse of international order. 

Where is international law when the so-called head of state is reportedly protected by dozens of Cuban security personnel rather than Venezuelan soldiers? Where is international law when human rights are violated and people are tortured and killed? 

Again, this is a good article, but it overlooks critical realities.

Venezuelans understand that the United States has strategic interests in oil, and many of us accept that this may be part of the price of recovering our freedom. Meanwhile, countries such as Iran, Russia, China, and Cuba have benefited from Venezuela‚Äôs resources for years. We will not apologize for preferring to do business with the United States if it helps restore democracy and stability. Yes, international order is changing. Has it fallen apart? Yes, but that happened way before the Americans got involved. Do not overlook the cry for freedom and liberty of the Venezuelan üáªüá™ people. We don‚Äôt eat oil for breakfast.
